778
00:28:32,798 --> 00:28:34,103
to know what
we're dealing with.

779
00:28:34,147 --> 00:28:35,714
But that's every call.

780
00:28:35,757 --> 00:28:37,367
It's a constant struggleto figure things out

781
00:28:37,411 --> 00:28:38,891
before it's too late.

782
00:28:41,328 --> 00:28:43,373
Uh, 7-Adam-19,
go to channel nine.

783
00:28:44,331 --> 00:28:45,941
Go for 7-Adam-19.

784
00:28:45,985 --> 00:28:47,726
Did you studypostpartum depression

785
00:28:47,769 --> 00:28:49,118
in your psych major?

786
00:28:49,162 --> 00:28:53,514
Yeah. PPD is fairly common,affects 1 in 8 new moms.

787
00:28:53,557 --> 00:28:56,038
In most cases, they feel tired,
alone, guilty.

788
00:28:56,082 --> 00:28:57,692
Some feel a lack of attachmentand then guilt

789
00:28:57,736 --> 00:28:58,998
for not feeling attached.

790
00:28:59,041 --> 00:29:03,002
Some are overwhelmed by paranoia --

791
00:29:03,045 --> 00:29:07,397
visions of horrible thingshappening to their own child.

792
00:29:07,441 --> 00:29:10,139
I see Rita turned downtreatment.

793
00:29:10,183 --> 00:29:12,489
That tells me she's probably  dealing with shame,

794
00:29:12,533 --> 00:29:14,622
trying to cope alone,isolating.

795
00:29:14,665 --> 00:29:16,189
Now add to that
the trauma

796
00:29:16,232 --> 00:29:18,495
of finding her childunresponsive.

797
00:29:18,539 --> 00:29:20,280
That could precipitatea mental break.

798
00:29:20,323 --> 00:29:22,543
If it's an extreme case of PPD,which is rare,

799
00:29:22,586 --> 00:29:25,328
she could be thinking aboutharming herself or her baby.

800
00:29:25,372 --> 00:29:26,634
Tim. Green Fiesta.

801
00:29:26,677 --> 00:29:27,809
Plates match.
That's our car.

802
00:29:27,853 --> 00:29:28,810
Nolan, we found
Rita's car.

803
00:29:28,854 --> 00:29:31,508
21000 block of Manningham.

804
00:29:31,552 --> 00:29:33,641
On our way.
Let's go.

805
00:29:33,684 --> 00:29:35,686
♪♪

806
00:29:38,167 --> 00:29:39,603
Lucy: Control, 7-Adam-19,

807
00:29:39,647 --> 00:29:41,997
we've located the Fiesta from
the revised Amber Alert.

808
00:29:42,041 --> 00:29:44,608
21000 block of Manningham.

809
00:29:44,652 --> 00:29:46,610
[ Pleasant music plays
on stereo]No sign of suspect or child.

810
00:29:49,439 --> 00:29:51,441
It's still hot.
She must have just ditched it.

811
00:29:51,485 --> 00:29:53,400
Man: Hey. You looking
for the driver?

812
00:29:53,443 --> 00:29:54,880
Tim: Yeah, you see
where she went?

813
00:29:54,923 --> 00:29:57,143
Nah. I was walking by
when she parked on the curb.

814
00:29:57,186 --> 00:29:59,145
How long ago?About five minutes.

815
00:29:59,188 --> 00:30:00,581
Enough time for Butch and I
to circle the block.

816
00:30:00,624 --> 00:30:03,062
Did she have
a baby with her?
No idea.

817
00:30:03,105 --> 00:30:05,629
I just watched her
totally demolish
that parking spot.

818
00:30:05,673 --> 00:30:07,283
[ Laughs ] Reminded me
of my ex-wife.

819
00:30:07,327 --> 00:30:08,937
Uh, yes, sir.
Please call us

820
00:30:08,981 --> 00:30:10,852
if you remember
anything else.
Okay.

821
00:30:10,896 --> 00:30:13,159
Control, 7-Adam-19, I got
the vehicle, unoccupied.

822
00:30:13,202 --> 00:30:15,161
Witness says the suspect hereless than five minutes ago.

823
00:30:15,204 --> 00:30:16,336
She's on foot.

824
00:30:16,379 --> 00:30:17,685
We need backup
and an airship

825
00:30:17,728 --> 00:30:18,773
to secure
a 10-block radius

826
00:30:18,817 --> 00:30:19,992
for a grid search.

827
00:30:21,602 --> 00:30:22,908
♪♪

828
00:30:22,951 --> 00:30:24,039
I don't like this.

829
00:30:24,083 --> 00:30:25,084
She wouldn't have abandoned
the car

830
00:30:25,127 --> 00:30:26,607
unless she stopped
for a reason.

831
00:30:26,650 --> 00:30:28,261
Odds are it won't be
a good one.

832
00:30:28,304 --> 00:30:29,915
We gotta find her fast.

833
00:30:33,788 --> 00:30:35,790
This is crazy.

834
00:30:35,834 --> 00:30:37,183
There's no way we find her
and the baby in time.

835
00:30:37,226 --> 00:30:39,315
We've got multiple units
and an airship searching.

836
00:30:39,359 --> 00:30:40,273
We will find them.

837
00:30:40,316 --> 00:30:41,752
How? They could be
anywhere.

838
00:30:41,796 --> 00:30:43,885
No. On foot with a newbornand a five-minute head start,

839
00:30:43,929 --> 00:30:45,582
she's definitely withinour grid.

840
00:30:45,626 --> 00:30:47,019
Someone will have seen her.

841
00:30:47,062 --> 00:30:50,457
Just...pray we find her beforeshe does something rash.

842
00:30:50,500 --> 00:30:59,727
♪♪

843
00:30:59,770 --> 00:31:00,815
Up on the right.

844
00:31:00,859 --> 00:31:03,078
[ Siren chirps ]

845
00:31:05,080 --> 00:31:07,126
Not her.

846
00:31:10,303 --> 00:31:11,478
Can I make a suggestion?

847
00:31:11,521 --> 00:31:12,914
Of course.

848
00:31:12,958 --> 00:31:14,829
Would it be helpful to have
Rita's husband

849
00:31:14,873 --> 00:31:18,050
brought down here
for -- for when she's found?

850
00:31:18,093 --> 00:31:19,573
That could be
dangerous.

851
00:31:19,616 --> 00:31:21,575
We don't know what the situationwas like at the house,

852
00:31:21,618 --> 00:31:24,012
and even if the baby's death
truly was accidental,

853
00:31:24,056 --> 00:31:25,840
there could have been
marital issues

854
00:31:25,884 --> 00:31:27,494
that added to Rita's PPD.

855
00:31:27,537 --> 00:31:29,191
We'd be introducing
a wildcard

856
00:31:29,235 --> 00:31:30,540
to an already tenuoussituation.

857
00:31:30,584 --> 00:31:32,151
Wait, so it's all on you?

858
00:31:32,194 --> 00:31:34,370
I mean, no matter what you find
when you get to her,

859
00:31:34,414 --> 00:31:35,502
you have to be ready to
deal with it?

860
00:31:35,545 --> 00:31:38,157
What -- What if you make
a mistake?

861
00:31:38,200 --> 00:31:39,985
We have to live with it.

862
00:31:40,028 --> 00:31:42,596
If we can.

863
00:31:42,639 --> 00:31:45,207
Pilot: All units, Air Three has
eyes on the suspect.

864
00:31:45,251 --> 00:31:46,295
Fourth Street Bridge.

865
00:31:46,339 --> 00:31:49,037
Repeat --
Fourth Street Bridge.

866
00:31:49,081 --> 00:31:51,257
She has the baby.
She's standing at the railing.

867
00:31:51,300 --> 00:31:53,824
Possible jumper.
Repeat, possible jumper.

868
00:31:53,868 --> 00:31:55,130
Here we go.

869
00:31:55,174 --> 00:31:57,263
Control, advise Fire we have
a possible jumper

870
00:31:57,306 --> 00:31:58,394
on Fourth Street Bridge.

871
00:31:58,438 --> 00:31:59,700
See if they havea crash pad available.

872
00:31:59,743 --> 00:32:03,051
We'll also need RA andbackup units, Code 2 high.

873
00:32:03,095 --> 00:32:09,362
♪♪

874
00:32:09,405 --> 00:32:12,278
[ Helicopter blades whirring ]

875
00:32:15,542 --> 00:32:17,370
[ Car doors close ]

876
00:32:17,413 --> 00:32:19,285
Maybe I should
stay back.

877
00:32:19,328 --> 00:32:20,677
Uh, it's up to you,

878
00:32:20,721 --> 00:32:22,070
but a friendly face
not in uniform

879
00:32:22,114 --> 00:32:23,854
might actually calm
the situation.

880
00:32:23,898 --> 00:32:25,291
How do you want to
play this?

881
00:32:25,334 --> 00:32:26,031
You go talk to her.

882
00:32:26,074 --> 00:32:27,336
You sure?

883
00:32:27,380 --> 00:32:28,947
Yeah, I'll step in
if I need to.

884
00:32:31,645 --> 00:32:34,561
W-Why -- Why Nolan?

885
00:32:34,604 --> 00:32:38,217
He has a way of connecting with
people in crisis situations.

886
00:32:38,260 --> 00:32:40,610
Hi, Rita.

887
00:32:40,654 --> 00:32:41,698
I'm John.

888
00:32:41,742 --> 00:32:42,699
[ Baby crying ]

889
00:32:42,743 --> 00:32:44,266
How do you know
my name?

890
00:32:44,310 --> 00:32:45,659
Uh, Ethan told me.

891
00:32:45,702 --> 00:32:48,053
He's very worried
about you.

892
00:32:48,096 --> 00:32:50,011
I'm fine.

893
00:32:50,055 --> 00:32:51,970
Who's that
you got there?

894
00:32:52,013 --> 00:32:53,275
Casey.

895
00:32:53,319 --> 00:32:54,581
This is Casey.

896
00:32:54,624 --> 00:32:56,017
Oh.

897
00:32:56,061 --> 00:32:57,714
Casey looks
a little bit cold.

898
00:32:57,758 --> 00:32:59,673
Why don't we bring her inside,
off the bridge?

899
00:32:59,716 --> 00:33:00,587
No.

900
00:33:00,630 --> 00:33:03,068
She's fine with
her mama.

901
00:33:03,111 --> 00:33:05,157
Do you mind if I just
make sure?

902
00:33:05,200 --> 00:33:06,375
Stay back.

903
00:33:06,419 --> 00:33:07,420
Okay, yeah.
I'll stay back.

904
00:33:07,463 --> 00:33:08,769
We -- We can just talk.

905
00:33:17,386 --> 00:33:18,170
Lucy: How's she doing?

906
00:33:18,213 --> 00:33:20,302
Uh, it's touch and go.

907
00:33:20,346 --> 00:33:22,000
What do you need?Keep them back.

908
00:33:22,043 --> 00:33:23,740
We don't want to
spook her.

909
00:33:23,784 --> 00:33:25,742
Okay.Nolan: No, I know it can
feel isolating,

910
00:33:25,786 --> 00:33:27,440
being a parent to
a newborn...

911
00:33:27,483 --> 00:33:28,571
She's not looking at
the baby.

912
00:33:28,615 --> 00:33:30,312
Nolan:
...so much to learn.

913
00:33:30,356 --> 00:33:32,010
[ Baby fusses ]You never feel like
what you're doing...

914
00:33:32,053 --> 00:33:33,576
She's trying to
convince herself

915
00:33:33,620 --> 00:33:35,317
that it's her baby
she's holding.

916
00:33:35,361 --> 00:33:37,928
Yeah. Deep down inside,
she knows it's not.

917
00:33:37,972 --> 00:33:40,018
What happens when
she figures out the truth?

918
00:33:40,061 --> 00:33:41,671
It's hard to say
for sure.

919
00:33:41,715 --> 00:33:43,195
It could break the spell or it
could send her over the edge,

920
00:33:43,238 --> 00:33:44,544
literally.

921
00:33:44,587 --> 00:33:46,328
Control, what's the ETA
on Fire?

922
00:33:46,372 --> 00:33:47,590
Dispatch: Three minutes.

923
00:33:47,634 --> 00:33:49,157
Might as well be
three hours.

924
00:33:49,201 --> 00:33:51,551
Nolan: Are you thirsty,
Rita?

925
00:33:51,594 --> 00:33:52,247
I can get you
some water.

926
00:33:52,291 --> 00:33:53,814
Nolan.

927
00:33:53,857 --> 00:33:55,294
Can I talk to her?

928
00:33:55,337 --> 00:33:56,469
Hey, Rita, I'm gonna
introduce you

929
00:33:56,512 --> 00:33:57,992
to my friend,
Angela, okay?

930
00:33:58,036 --> 00:33:59,472
Okay.

931
00:33:59,515 --> 00:34:00,995
Hi, Rita.

932
00:34:01,039 --> 00:34:03,084
I'm here to help.

933
00:34:03,128 --> 00:34:04,129
Is this Casey?

934
00:34:05,478 --> 00:34:07,045
Yes.

935
00:34:07,088 --> 00:34:08,524
I love that name.

936
00:34:08,568 --> 00:34:12,311
My fiancé and I can't agree
on a name for our baby.

937
00:34:12,354 --> 00:34:13,921
How did you choose?

938
00:34:13,964 --> 00:34:16,097
I don't know.

939
00:34:16,141 --> 00:34:18,230
When she was born, she just
looked like a Casey.

940
00:34:18,273 --> 00:34:21,102
[ Baby fussing ]

941
00:34:21,146 --> 00:34:22,756
How far along are you?

942
00:34:22,799 --> 00:34:24,497
14 weeks.

943
00:34:24,540 --> 00:34:27,108
I'm already scared
about giving birth.

944
00:34:27,152 --> 00:34:28,283
The pain.

945
00:34:28,327 --> 00:34:30,590
Don't worry about
the pain.

946
00:34:30,633 --> 00:34:34,289
Once they put your baby
in your arms

947
00:34:34,333 --> 00:34:37,727
and you look down into
those beautiful eyes,

948
00:34:37,771 --> 00:34:39,555
it was all worth it.

949
00:34:39,599 --> 00:34:43,124
I heard all newborns
have blue eyes.

950
00:34:43,168 --> 00:34:44,647
Not Casey.

951
00:34:44,691 --> 00:34:48,042
Dark brown,
right from the start.

952
00:34:48,086 --> 00:34:50,784
The most amazing
head of hair.

953
00:34:50,827 --> 00:34:51,654
I hope
if I have a daughter,

954
00:34:51,698 --> 00:34:53,439
she's born with hair.

955
00:34:53,482 --> 00:34:56,442
My cousin's little girl,
she was bald

956
00:34:56,485 --> 00:34:58,487
for like the first
18 months.

957
00:34:58,531 --> 00:35:00,141
Everyone thought
she was a boy.

958
00:35:00,185 --> 00:35:01,403
I love putting

959
00:35:01,447 --> 00:35:03,884
Casey's hair
in little pigtails.

960
00:35:03,927 --> 00:35:07,757
She always fights me,
but she looks so cute.

961
00:35:07,801 --> 00:35:12,153
Rita, can you do something
for me?

962
00:35:12,197 --> 00:35:13,763
Can you look at Casey?

963
00:35:13,807 --> 00:35:15,896
Just look in those pretty,
brown eyes.

964
00:35:15,939 --> 00:35:18,377
[ Baby crying ]

965
00:35:18,420 --> 00:35:19,421
No.

966
00:35:19,465 --> 00:35:20,596
Please, Rita.

967
00:35:20,640 --> 00:35:22,337
I need you to
look in her eyes.

968
00:35:22,381 --> 00:35:24,426
[ Helicopter blades whirring ]

969
00:35:27,951 --> 00:35:30,606
[ Crying continues ]

970
00:35:32,391 --> 00:35:35,959
It's not Casey,
is it?

971
00:35:36,003 --> 00:35:37,961
[ Voice breaking ] No.

972
00:35:38,005 --> 00:35:40,138
No.

973
00:35:40,181 --> 00:35:42,792
Here. I got her.

974
00:35:42,836 --> 00:35:45,491
I'll get her back to
her mother, okay?

975
00:35:49,103 --> 00:35:51,453
Tell her [Sniffles]
I'm sorry.

976
00:35:53,673 --> 00:35:55,065
Nolan:
Thank you, Rita.

977
00:35:55,109 --> 00:35:57,242
That was a very brave thingyou did,

978
00:35:57,285 --> 00:35:59,287
and now I need youto come with me, okay?

979
00:36:00,593 --> 00:36:02,899
My baby died.

980
00:36:02,943 --> 00:36:04,336
I know.

981
00:36:04,379 --> 00:36:05,511
I'm so sorry.

982
00:36:05,554 --> 00:36:07,730
[ Sobbing ]

983
00:36:07,774 --> 00:36:11,647
Come on. Come on.

984
00:36:13,519 --> 00:36:15,999
[ Baby cooing ]

985
00:36:16,043 --> 00:36:23,311
♪♪

986
00:36:29,274 --> 00:36:31,711
[ Engine shuts off ]

987
00:36:31,754 --> 00:36:33,669
Well, thank you
for today.

988
00:36:33,713 --> 00:36:35,976
This is an experience
I will not forget.

989
00:36:36,019 --> 00:36:38,108
Well, we should schedule

990
00:36:38,152 --> 00:36:40,067
another one of theselittle ride alongs

991
00:36:40,110 --> 00:36:41,895
so that we can continuethe conversation.

992
00:36:41,938 --> 00:36:43,505
Oh, that won't be
necessary.

993
00:36:43,549 --> 00:36:44,637
[ Camera clicks off ]

994
00:36:44,680 --> 00:36:47,205
The book's already written,
isn't it?

995
00:36:47,248 --> 00:36:49,119
I sent it to my publisher
last week.

996
00:36:49,163 --> 00:36:50,599
Mm.
What?

997
00:36:50,643 --> 00:36:52,122
Then what was today about,
then?

998
00:36:52,166 --> 00:36:54,168
Just an anecdote
for the book tour?

999
00:36:54,212 --> 00:36:56,562
No, I didn't know the day was
gonna end up the way it did.

1000
00:36:56,605 --> 00:36:58,520
But how do you write a book
about policing

1001
00:36:58,564 --> 00:36:59,608
without having seen it
up close?

1002
00:36:59,652 --> 00:37:01,610
Oh, I have seen it.
Believe me.

1003
00:37:01,654 --> 00:37:03,133
Today may have been
my first ride along,

1004
00:37:03,177 --> 00:37:04,222
but it was not my first time

1005
00:37:04,265 --> 00:37:05,788
sitting in the back seat
of a cop car.

1006
00:37:05,832 --> 00:37:08,138
I see, but if you're going to
fix an engine,

1007
00:37:08,182 --> 00:37:09,792
don't you think it would be
helpful to look under the hood?

1008
00:37:09,836 --> 00:37:12,012
That is a flawed analogy,
Officer Nolan,

1009
00:37:12,055 --> 00:37:13,492
because a car is not
actively trying to

1010
00:37:13,535 --> 00:37:14,710
keep you from fixing it.

1011
00:37:16,103 --> 00:37:17,452
Uh, excuse me.

1012
00:37:19,759 --> 00:37:22,762
Look, I get that the path
to real change

1013
00:37:22,805 --> 00:37:24,764
seems almost impossible.

1014
00:37:24,807 --> 00:37:27,723
I mean, police departments are
pros at circling the wagons

1015
00:37:27,767 --> 00:37:30,291
when public opinion
turns against them.

1016
00:37:30,335 --> 00:37:33,076
But I promise you,

1017
00:37:33,120 --> 00:37:35,427
the only way
things really will change

1018
00:37:35,470 --> 00:37:37,820
is if cops get on board.

1019
00:37:37,864 --> 00:37:39,257
I agree.

1020
00:37:39,300 --> 00:37:41,694
But cops only act when activists
make so much noise,

1021
00:37:41,737 --> 00:37:43,304
they cannot be ignored.

1022
00:37:43,348 --> 00:37:44,827
Like in Camden.

1023
00:37:44,871 --> 00:37:47,177
Look, you're talking to
two police officers

1024
00:37:47,221 --> 00:37:48,831
who would like to
see things change,

1025
00:37:48,875 --> 00:37:51,834
and we're not the only ones at
the station that feels this way.

1026
00:37:51,878 --> 00:37:55,316
I just think that...
uh, maybe you could benefit

1027
00:37:55,360 --> 00:37:57,753
from some of our insights.

1028
00:38:01,931 --> 00:38:02,802
Alright.

1029
00:38:04,020 --> 00:38:05,674
You sold me.

1030
00:38:05,718 --> 00:38:07,676
Great.
I'll tell Sergeant Grey.

1031
00:38:07,720 --> 00:38:09,243
I'm sure he'd love to
be part of the conversation.

1032
00:38:09,287 --> 00:38:10,853
Oh, thank you.

1033
00:38:10,897 --> 00:38:13,726
And thank you both for
the ride along.

1034
00:38:13,769 --> 00:38:15,336
I will see you in class.

1035
00:38:15,380 --> 00:38:16,642
Looking forward.

1036
